<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DAR 08</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence to the Enquiry into Democracy and Development in Burma, submitted by the Burma Relief Centre</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission by Burma Relief Centre, an NGO with 25 years’ experience in capacity building of civil society and currently receiving DFID support through Christian Aid, contains the following key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID has provided almost no support to ethnic civil society in Burma’s conflict zones, despite their vitally important work in promoting sustainable development and rights protection, and in building community based structures to address humanitarian needs in remote areas. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">During this critical time of potential peace-building in Burma, DFID is strongly advised to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increase direct support to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnic civil society grou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ps</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To enable them to raise community concerns and input policy recommendations into political negotiations so that just, sustainable solutions can be achieved to end the conflict.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To ensure that humanitarian needs in these conflict areas continue to be met, and existing community social service structures are built upon and not ignored and replaced. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Detailed submission </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC has been providing humanitarian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aid and supporting the development of civil society in Burma for 25 years. BRC currently has over 70 community-based partner organizations working mainly in the ethnic states of Burma, in five</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> program areas: health, community development, environment and human rights, women’s development and media.  BRC’s current annual budget is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">US$2.5 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. BRC has received funds from DFID through Christian Aid’s Basic Health Care Project since 2011.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC has 15 staff, mostly from Burma’s ethnic states, and three offices:  one in northern Thailand, one on the Thai-Burma border, and one in Mon State of Burma.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC has played a significant role in supporting the development of civil society in Burma’s ethnic states over the past 15-20 years. During this time, civil society groups, receiving support cross-border due to the restrictions in-country, developed extensive humanitarian programming in their respective states, addressing food, health and education needs.  During military rule, they were also the main voices to the outside world of the human rights situation in their areas. Since the 2010 elections, some of these groups have begun operating more openly inside Burma, but others are not yet able to do so, either due to ongoing restrictions or ongoing conflict. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some key achievements of these ethnic civil society groups in recent years have been: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ability to address critical health needs in remote conflict areas. In 2012, indigenous health organizations reached a target population over half a million in conflict affected areas of Burma, and trained almost 3,000 community health workers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Promotion of women’s rights among ethnic communities which are traditionally extremely patriarchal. This has included extensive programming against sexual and gender based violence, including documentation and advocacy against the Burmese military’s use of rape as a weapon of war. </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development of a broad media network in the ethnic states, enabling access to information for remote marginalized communities in their own languages, and providing unique reporting on the ongoing peace process.  </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Widespread community awareness of the need for environmental protection and sustainable development, which has led to the stopping of controversial development projects, such as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Myitsone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> dam on the Irrawaddy river in 2011, and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tamanthi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> dam on the Chindwin river in 2013. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development of grassroots ethnic farmers’ networks to address issues of widespread</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> land grabbing. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development of inter-ethnic alliances in many sectors, which are promoting ethnic reconciliation, for example the Women’s League of Burma, Burma Rivers Network, Burma News International, Ethnic Community Development Forum. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite the effectiveness and importance of this cross-border ethnic civil society work, it has received almost no support at all from DFID.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that it is crucially important to maintain support for these ethnic civil society groups at this time of transition in Burma, in order to promote sustainable peace, as well as to address humanitarian needs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> The need to support ethnic civil society to promote sustainable peace</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current “peace process” in Burma is extremely fragile. Although all but two of the main ethnic armed groups in Burma have signed ceasefires since 2011, government forces have not withdrawn from frontline areas and are continuing to launch military offensives against ethnic forces, including those with ceasefires. Even though political dialogue has yet to begin, the government has used the pretext of “peace” to promote foreign investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and sell off the rich natural resources </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in ethnic areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ethnic resistance umbrella group, the United Nationalities Federal Council (UNFC) is calling for political dialogue and constitutional reform outside parliament, as a means to achieving federalism. However, there is no sign that the government will concede to this demand. Instead it has been seeking to persuade individual armed groups to come under the 2008 unitary constitution, and offering them economic incentives. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fostering serious divisi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ons among the ethnic groups, with some leaders being lured by business concessions, and some refusing to be “bought” and sticking to their political demands. Such divisions will not foster peace, but will very likely lead to new factions splitting away and reverting to war as the only means to achieve their political aspirations.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Before the various parties revert to war, it is thus urgently needed to maximize the opportunities provided by the current “peace talks” to begin addressing the ethnic demands for equal rights and federalism.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crucial to this process is ethnic civil society. However, they have been so far almost entirely excluded from the formal peace process. They </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have developed considerable expertise in key issues that need to be addressed to ensure durable peace - land rights, natural resource management, sustainable development, democratic governance, justice and accountability mechanisms, health and education systems, gender equality etc.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many civil society groups have begun a parallel “track two” peace process in their respective ethnic states to broaden participation and bring some of these issues to the negotiating table. They have begun formulating policy recommendations for ethnic dialogue stakeholders, raising public awareness of the issues at stake, and promoting transparency around the peace process. This has started to gain positive recognitio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n from some “track one” actors, and some civil society members are starting to be invited into formal technical teams to provide policy advice.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, there has so far been little international funding support for this “track two” process, despite its vitally important role. Most international donors, including D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ID, are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supporting various government-approved peace support initiatives built around the “track one” negotiations, despite the lack of political progress.  It is urgently needed to give direct support to ethnic civil society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">push </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">independently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for meaningful political dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mobilize their communities around this process. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s interest in assisting natural resource management in Burma would also be served by supporting ethnic civil society groups to push for federal power sharing over this critical issue during the peace process. Power over natural resources is a key factor driving the conflict, and without addressing this issue, resource extraction in the ethnic areas will never be secure. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By only supporting Burmese government-approved peace support initiatives, DFID risks letting it appear that the UK is only interested in supporting one side of the conflict, and not in forging real peace. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should also take care to consult directly with ethnic civil society when supporting such government approved initiatives. For example, in mid-2012, DFID was planning to support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preparations for repatriation of Shan refugees into an insecure war-zone, until a public denouncement of the plan by Shan civil society groups forced the program to be halted.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The need to support ethnic civil society to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">build on and develop social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in their areas</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Naypidaw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> government is poised to start expanding central government-managed social services into ethnic areas which have already set up their own social service structures, often managed at the community level, based on their own needs, language and religion.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this time of uncertain transition, it is recommended that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID employ a dual strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in providing support in the sector of social services in ethnic areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continued </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">direct support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to indigenous community health and education programs in remote conflict areas remains essential. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is in line with DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commitment to fulfilling the Millennium Development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Goals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regarding health, DFID has committed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK’s health-related frameworks for results, 1) for improving reproductive, maternal and newborn health and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2) for malaria. While DFID is supporting one ‘cross-border’ ethnic health program as part of an emergency health care project until 2014, it denied support to an expanding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reproductive and child health care program in Shan State and supports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">none of the other existing ‘cross-border’ primary health care programs providing essential services for both malaria and maternal and child health care. It is imperative that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such interventions, which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will have long-term impact by improving maternal and child mortality rates in this region, continue to receive funds as long as necessary.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second strategy is support for governance-related issues in the social sectors. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">espite the government’s public commitment to public health care and universal health care coverage, its approach remains highly centralized and inefficient, showing few signs of including or empowering local communities. The multi-ethnic Health Convergence Core Group (HCCG, comprised of all major ethnic health organizations and CBOs providing services in the conflict-affected zones and representing a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">500,000+ target population) has in its official Statement of Principles (2013) requested that “communities and community-based health organizations must be involved in the decision-making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process and the implementation of health care services in the Ethnic States”. It is important that participatory dialogue and collaborative efforts between the government and groups like the HCCG be prioritized.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Failure to invest adequate time and appropriate resources to address the complex issue of future convergence between these different structures risks inciting community resentment and fuelling further conflict. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risks wasting decades of investment in existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social service structures by ‘re-inventing the wheel’ and leaving in their place a top-down, ineffective and unnecessarily expensive system. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Documentation by women’s organizations can be seen on the website of the Women’s League of Burma:  </span><a href="http://www.womenofburma.org"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.womenofburma.org</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> See the website of Burma News International: </span><a href="http://www.bnionline.net"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.bnionline.net</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">and </span><a href="http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.mmpeacemonitor.org</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> See: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.shanhumanrights.org/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=345:27-august-2012&amp;catid=75:action-updae</span></p></body></html>